# git status
# git status --short
 OR
# git status -s
C:\Users\ryarrapu\Git-ProGit>git status --short
 D clone-remote
?? git-clone-git-remote-notes
?? git-config-notes
?? git-unborn-branch-notes

D = Deleted file
? = New file (not yet tracked by git)
A = Added to staging area (Git considers it for next commit)
M = Modified
Did you notice, "git status -s" output has two columns of "?" before filenames-column?
First column is about files in staging area = files marked for next commit
Second column is about files in working dir = newly created files or modified-or-deleted-files which are tracked by git.

C:\Users\ryarrapu\Git-ProGit>git status -s
 D clone-remote
A  git-clone-git-remote-notes
?? git-config-notes
?? git-unborn-branch-notes

C:\Users\ryarrapu\Git-ProGit>git add git-config-notes

C:\Users\ryarrapu\Git-ProGit>git status -s
 D clone-remote
A  git-clone-git-remote-notes
A  git-config-notes
?? git-unborn-branch-notes

C:\Users\ryarrapu\Git-ProGit>echo "\n*******************\n">>git-config-notes

C:\Users\ryarrapu\Git-ProGit>git status -s
 D clone-remote
A  git-clone-git-remote-notes
AM git-config-notes
?? git-unborn-branch-notes

C:\Users\ryarrapu\Git-ProGit>git add git-config-notes

C:\Users\ryarrapu\Git-ProGit>git status -s
 D clone-remote
A  git-clone-git-remote-notes
A  git-config-notes
?? git-unborn-branch-notes

When do you see MM in the first and 2nd columns of "git status -s"?

C:\Users\ryarrapu\Git-ProGit>echo "That's it." >> unborn-branch.txt

C:\Users\ryarrapu\Git-ProGit>git status -s
 M unborn-branch.txt

C:\Users\ryarrapu\Git-ProGit>git add unborn-branch.txt

C:\Users\ryarrapu\Git-ProGit>git status -s
M  unborn-branch.txt

C:\Users\ryarrapu\Git-ProGit>echo "Done" >> unborn-branch.txt

C:\Users\ryarrapu\Git-ProGit>git status -s
MM unborn-branch.txt


